  "text": "Previous findings in H10 cells 7 suggest that NDPK B/G‚ê§‚ê•mediated phosphate transfer is a mechanism for receptorindependent G protein activation. Here we studied the effect of a His to Leu replacement at position 266 in G‚ê§ 1 on NDPK B/G‚ê§‚ê•-mediated G s activation, using cAMP as reporter. Experiments were performed in H10-WT cells and H10 cells with a 3-fold overexpression of NDPK B (NDPKœ© cells 7 ). cAMP production was determined in the presence of the ‚ê§-adrenoceptor (‚ê§AR) inverse agonist propranolol to block spontaneous or constitutive ‚ê§AR activity. Infection of H10 cells with increasing doses of AdG‚ê£ s combined with either AdG‚ê§ 1 WT‚ê• 2 or AdG‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 resulted in similar amounts of protein expression ( Figure 2A ). Overexpression of the G‚ê§ 1 ‚ê• 2 variants did not alter of NDPK B expression ( Figure 2A ) nor the total NDPK activity in these cells (GFP: 93.7œÆ4.3, G‚ê§ 1 WT‚ê• 2 : 90.5œÆ3.6, G‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 : 91.7œÆ4.3 nmol/min*mg). In H10-WT cells, increasing amounts of G‚ê£ s were associated with a linear increase cAMP accumulation. However, coexpression of G‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 reduced this effect by œ∑30% compared with G‚ê§ 1 WT‚ê• 2 at each level of G‚ê£ s ( Figure 2B ). In NDPKœ© cells, the elevated NDPK B content increased the G‚ê£ s -mediated cAMP synthesis [CITATION_1] and enhanced the inhibitory effect of G‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 ( Figure 2C ). At the highest G‚ê£ s expression (MOI 100), the cAMP content in G‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 -infected NDPKœ© cells amounted to 45.0œÆ3.7% (nœ≠4, PœΩ0.001) of that seen in G‚ê§ 1 WT‚ê• 2 -infected cells. Thus, the observed difference between G‚ê§ 1 WT‚ê• 2 and G‚ê§ 1 H266L‚ê• 2 overexpressing cells in basal cAMP synthesis apparently depends on both the level of G‚ê£ s and NDPK B.",
